modifies the AGPLv3 as it applies to the Program by providing an exception
for qualifying Plugins, as defined below.

  The purpose of this Exception is to allow third-party developers to
create Plugins for the Program under licenses of their choosing, without
being subject to the copyleft requirements of the AGPLv3, while ensuring
that the copyleft protections of the AGPLv3 remain fully enforceable
against any work that modifies, extends, or derives from the Program in
a manner that goes beyond the defined Plugin interface.

  This Exception does not apply to the Program itself, which remains
governed exclusively by the AGPLv3 without modification.


                        1. DEFINITIONS

  "Plugin" means a software module that satisfies ALL of the following
conditions (the "Qualification Criteria"):

    (a) Interface Compliance. The module's primary class must be a proper
        subclass of the Program's PluginInterface abstract base class, as
        defined in the source file "plugins/core/base.py" of the Program.
        The subclass must implement all abstract methods required by
        PluginInterface, namely initialize() and shutdown(), and must
        provide the constructor parameters plugin_id, name, and version.
        A Plugin may additionally implement one or more of the following
        optional interfaces (also defined in "plugins/core/base.py"):

          (i)   ServiceProvider: to register discoverable services with
                the Program's ServiceRegistry. A Plugin that implements
                ServiceProvider must implement the abstract methods
                get_service_name() and get_service_interface(), and the
                service it provides must be consumed by the Program
                exclusively through the ServiceRegistry's get() or
                get_by_interface() methods.

          (ii)  UIExtensionProvider: to inject UI content into designated
                extension points (slots) in the Program's templates. A
                Plugin that implements UIExtensionProvider must implement
                the abstract method get_ui_extensions(), which returns a
                list of UIExtension objects. Each UIExtension declares a
                target slot, rendering method (inline HTML or Django
                template), and optional context_callback for providing
                template context data. The Program renders these
                extensions through the "plugin_extensions" template tag
                library. A Plugin may only inject content into slots
                that the Program explicitly defines in its templates; it
                must not modify, override, or replace any template,
                template block, or UI component that belongs to the
                Program.

          (iii) URLProvider: to dynamically register URL patterns with
                the Program's routing system. A Plugin that implements
                URLProvider must implement the abstract method
                get_url_patterns(), which returns a list of dictionaries
                specifying URL prefix, Django URL conf module path,
                namespace, and section (admin, provider, or public).
                The Program includes these patterns through its
                dynamic_urls module. A Plugin may only register URLs
                under the prefix and namespace it declares; it must not
                override, replace, or intercept URL patterns that belong
                to the Program or to other Plugins.

    (b) Standard Loading. The module must be loaded exclusively through
        the Program's standard PluginManager mechanisms, as implemented in
        "plugins/core/plugin_manager.py" and "plugins/plugin_manager.py"
        of the Program. This includes:
          (i)   Registration via the plugins.toml configuration file; or
          (ii)  Discovery through the PluginManager's directory scanning
                mechanism; or
          (iii) Registration through the Program's CLI management command
                ("python manage.py plugin install").
        A Plugin may register as a Django application (via an apps.py
        AppConfig) in the Program's INSTALLED_APPS setting for the
        purposes of Django model discovery, template discovery, and
        migration management, provided that such registration is
        documented in the Plugin's installation instructions and the
        Plugin's Django app label is distinct from the Program's core
        app labels.

    (c) Communication Through Defined Interfaces. The module may
        communicate with the Program ONLY through the following defined
        interfaces:
          (i)    Methods defined in the PluginInterface abstract base class;
          (ii)   The EventHook mechanism (register_hook, trigger_hook) as
                 provided by the Program's PluginManager;
          (iii)  Django signals that the Program explicitly exposes for
                 plugin use, as documented in the Program's source code;
          (iv)   The Plugin API endpoints defined in the Program's
                 django_integration.py module;
          (v)    The PluginConfiguration model for storing plugin-specific
                 key-value configuration data;
          (vi)   The ServiceProvider and ServiceRegistry mechanism, whereby
                 a Plugin may register services that the Program discovers
                 and consumes through the ServiceRegistry. The Program's
                 core code must not import or depend on any Plugin's
                 internal modules directly; it must access Plugin-provided
                 services exclusively through the ServiceRegistry;
          (vii)  The UIExtensionProvider mechanism, whereby a Plugin may
                 declare UIExtension objects that the Program renders in
                 predefined template slots via the "plugin_extensions"
                 Django template tag library. A Plugin may use the
                 context_callback attribute of UIExtension to provide
                 dynamic context data for template rendering;
          (viii) The URLProvider mechanism, whereby a Plugin may declare
                 URL patterns that the Program dynamically includes in its
                 routing configuration via the dynamic_urls module. The
                 Program resolves and serves these URLs through the
                 Plugin's own Django views;
          (ix)   The Django app registry (apps.get_model()) for accessing
                 models defined by the Program's core applications, used
                 solely for querying data through the Django ORM. A Plugin
                 must not modify the schema of, or create migrations for,
                 models belonging to the Program's core applications;
          (x)    The PluginRecord model for tracking plugin installation
                 state, and the PluginConfiguration model for storing
                 plugin-specific key-value configuration data. A Plugin
                 may read and write its own PluginConfiguration entries
                 but must not modify entries belonging to other Plugins.

    (d) No Modification of Core Program. The module must NOT:
          (i)    Modify, patch, override, or monkey-patch any source code
                 of the Program, including but not limited to: core modules,
                 Django models, views, URL configurations, middleware,
                 signal handlers, or management commands that are part of
                 the Program;
          (ii)   Replace or substantially rewrite any core functionality
                 of the Program;
          (iii)  Alter the Program's database schema or create database
                 migrations that modify tables belonging to the Program's
                 core applications (as opposed to creating new tables for
                 the Plugin's own data);
          (iv)   Modify the Program's settings, configuration, or
                 initialization process at runtime in a manner that changes
                 the Program's behavior for users who do not use the Plugin;
          (v)    Inject, replace, or remove Django middleware, URL patterns,
                 or signal handlers that belong to the Program.

        For the avoidance of doubt, the following actions do NOT constitute
        "modification of the core Program":
          - Registering a Plugin's Django app in INSTALLED_APPS;
          - Declaring UIExtension objects that inject content into the
            Program's predefined template slots;
          - Declaring URL patterns through the URLProvider interface;
          - Reading data from the Program's models via apps.get_model()
            or Django's ORM;
          - Writing to the PluginConfiguration model for the Plugin's
            own configuration entries.

    (e) No Substantial Copying. The module must NOT contain, embed, or
        reproduce substantial portions of the Program's source code. A
        Plugin may reference the Program's public API and data structures
        through normal import and inheritance mechanisms, but must not
        duplicate the Program's implementation logic.

    (f) Independence. The Program must remain fully functional without
        the Plugin installed. The Plugin's absence must not cause the
        Program to fail to start, crash, or lose any core functionality
        that existed prior to the Plugin's installation. A Plugin may
        add new functionality, but must not remove or break existing
        functionality. For Plugins that implement ServiceProvider, the
        Program must gracefully handle the absence of the service by
        degrading functionality (e.g., disabling features that depend
        on the service, returning safe default values, or logging
        warnings) rather than raising unhandled exceptions.

    (g) Distinct Purpose. The Plugin must serve a purpose that is
        distinct from and supplementary to the Program's core
        functionality. A module that replicates, replaces, or
        substantially duplicates the Program's core features is not a
        Plugin, regardless of whether it technically satisfies the
        interface requirements of subsection (a).


                    2. GRANT OF EXCEPTION

  Notwithstanding the copyleft provisions of Sections 5 and 13 of the
AGPLv3, a work that qualifies as a Plugin under Section 1 of this
Exception is NOT considered a work "based on the Program" solely by
reason of its interaction with the Program through the defined Plugin
interfaces. Accordingly, you may license such a Plugin under any terms
of your choosing, provided that:

    (a) The Plugin satisfies all Qualification Criteria set forth in
        Section 1 at all times during its distribution and use;

    (b) You comply with the notice requirements of Section 3 of this
        Exception; and

    (c) You do not distribute the Plugin combined with the Program in
        a manner that would cause the Program itself to become subject
        to terms inconsistent with the AGPLv3.

  This Exception applies only to the Plugin itself. It does not extend
to the Program, to any modifications of the Program, or to any
combined work formed by aggregating the Program with a Plugin. The
Program, and any modifications thereto, remain governed by the AGPLv3
without exception.


                    3. NOTICE REQUIREMENTS

  Any Plugin distributed under the terms of this Exception must include
the following notices:

    (a) Source Code Notice. Each source file of the Plugin must include
        a prominent comment at the beginning of the file containing:

          (i)   A statement identifying the work as a Plugin for the
                ZASCA program;
          (ii)  The Plugin's own license terms; and
          (iii) The following declaration:

            "This is a plugin for the ZASCA program. ZASCA is licensed
             under the GNU Affero General Public License, Version 3
             (AGPLv3). This plugin is NOT part of ZASCA and is NOT
             licensed under the AGPLv3. The AGPLv3 applies to ZASCA
             itself, not to this plugin. This plugin uses the ZASCA
             Plugin Exception to the AGPLv3 for its interaction with
             ZASCA."

    (b) Documentation Notice. Any documentation, README, or
        distribution materials for the Plugin must prominently state:

          (i)   That the work is a Plugin for the ZASCA program;
          (ii)  That ZASCA is licensed under the AGPLv3;
          (iii) That the Plugin is NOT part of ZASCA and is NOT
                subject to the AGPLv3 by virtue of the ZASCA Plugin
                Exception;
          (iv)  The Plugin's own license terms; and
          (v)   That the AGPLv3 applies to ZASCA itself, not to the
                Plugin.

    (c) Runtime Notice. If the Plugin provides any user-facing
        interface (including but not limited to: web pages, API
        responses, CLI output, or log messages), it must display or
        include a notice indicating that it is a Plugin for ZASCA and
        that ZASCA's license (AGPLv3) does not apply to the Plugin.

    (d) Visual Interface Attribution. In addition to the source code
        and documentation notices required by subsections (a) and (b),
        any Plugin that injects, renders, or otherwise presents content
        in the Program's visual user interface MUST provide clear,
        visible attribution within that interface itself. This
        requirement applies regardless of whether the attribution is
        technically feasible at the code level alone, and is intended
        to ensure that end users can identify the origin of UI
        elements they interact with. Specifically:

          (i)   Modal Dialogs and Pop-ups. Any modal dialog, pop-up,
                overlay, or similar intrusive UI element injected by a
                Plugin must display a visible label or badge indicating
                that it originates from the Plugin. This label must be
                present within the visual content of the dialog itself
                (for example, in the dialog header, footer, or a
                clearly visible badge), not merely in the underlying
                HTML source code, comments, or developer tools. The
                label must include at minimum the Plugin's name and a
                statement that the content is provided by a third-party
                Plugin (e.g., "Provided by [Plugin Name] (ZASCA
                Plugin)").

          (ii)  Injected UI Panels and Widgets. Any panel, widget,
                sidebar section, card, or other non-modal UI component
                that a Plugin injects into the Program's interface
                through the UIExtensionProvider mechanism or any other
                means must include a visible attribution element. This
                may take the form of a header label, footer note, or
                icon badge that identifies the Plugin as the source of
                the content. The attribution must be reasonably
                prominent and not hidden behind hover states, tooltips,
                or expandable sections.

          (iii) Notifications and Toast Messages. Any notification,
                toast message, alert banner, or similar transient UI
                element produced by a Plugin must identify the Plugin
                as its source, either within the message text itself or
                through an adjacent label or icon.

          (iv)  Pages and Views Served by the Plugin. Any full page or
                view that a Plugin serves through the URLProvider
                mechanism must include a visible notice (such as a
                footer, header badge, or sidebar indicator) stating
                that the page is provided by the Plugin and is not part
                of ZASCA's core interface.

          (v)   General Principle. The overarching requirement is that
                no UI content injected by a Plugin may appear to the
                end user as though it is a native part of the ZASCA
                program. The attribution must be sufficient for a
                typical user to distinguish Plugin-provided UI elements
                from ZASCA's core interface elements. Minimal or
                hard-to-notice attributions (such as light-colored
                small text, hidden metadata, or code comments) do not
                satisfy this requirement. The attribution must be
                visually apparent under normal usage conditions without
                requiring the user to inspect source code, use
                developer tools, or perform any special action.


                    4. RECLASSIFICATION AND TERMINATION

    (a) Automatic Reclassification. If a work that purports to be a
        Plugin fails to satisfy any of the Qualification Criteria in
        Section 1, it is NOT a Plugin for the purposes of this
        Exception. Such a work shall be deemed a modification of or
        a work based on the Program, and the full terms of the AGPLv3
        shall apply to it without exception, including but not limited
        to the copyleft requirements of Sections 5 and 13.

    (b) No Retroactive Cure. A work that initially qualifies as a
        Plugin but is subsequently modified in a manner that causes it
        to fail any Qualification Criterion immediately loses the
        benefit of this Exception. The Exception may not be regained
        for that work by reverting the non-conforming changes, unless
        the copyright holders of the Program explicitly grant
        permission in writing.

    (c) Burden of Proof. Any party claiming the benefit of this
        Exception bears the burden of demonstrating that their work
        satisfies all Qualification Criteria. In case of doubt, a work
        shall be presumed NOT to qualify as a Plugin, and the AGPLv3
        shall apply in full.

    (d) Bad Faith. A work that is designed or structured primarily to
        circumvent the copyleft requirements of the AGPLv3, rather
        than to serve a legitimate supplementary purpose through the
        Program's Plugin interface, shall not qualify as a Plugin
        regardless of its technical compliance with the Qualification
        Criteria. Factors indicating bad faith include but are not
        limited to:
          (i)    The work duplicates core functionality of the Program
                 while implementing it through the Plugin interface
                 solely to avoid AGPLv3 obligations;
          (ii)   The work serves as a wrapper or shim that exposes the
                 Program's core functionality under a different license;
          (iii)  The work is designed to be inseparable from the Program
                 in practice, despite being technically loadable as a
                 Plugin;
          (iv)   The work's stated purpose is substantially identical
                 to the Program's stated purpose.


                    5. SCOPE AND LIMITATIONS

    (a) This Exception applies only to the Program known as ZASCA, as
        identified by its copyright holders. It does not apply to any
        other software licensed under the AGPLv3.

    (b) This Exception does not waive, modify, or limit any provision
        of the AGPLv3 except as explicitly stated herein. All
        provisions of the AGPLv3 that are not modified by this
        Exception remain in full force and effect.

    (c) This Exception does not grant any rights to use the trade
        names, trademarks, service marks, or product names of the
        Program's copyright holders, except as required to comply with
        the notice requirements of Section 3.

    (d) The copyright holders of the Program reserve the right to
        update or modify this Exception in future versions of the
        Program. Any such update shall not affect the status of Plugins
        that qualified under a previous version of this Exception at
        the time of their distribution.

    (e) If any provision of this Exception is held to be invalid or
        unenforceable, the remaining provisions shall remain in effect,
        and the invalid provision shall be modified to the minimum
        extent necessary to make it valid and enforceable while
        preserving the intent of preventing the use of the Plugin
        interface to circumvent the AGPLv3.


                    6. INTERPRETATION

  This Exception shall be interpreted in light of its purpose: to
permit genuine Plugins that extend the Program through its defined
Plugin interface to be licensed independently, while preserving the
copyleft protections of the AGPLv3 against any work that modifies,
derives from, or circumvents the Program's intended licensing
structure.

  Where ambiguity exists in the application of this Exception, the
interpretation that best preserves the copyleft protections of the
AGPLv3 shall prevail. The grant of an exception for Plugins is a
limited carve-out from the AGPLv3's copyleft requirements, and any
ambiguity in the scope of that carve-out shall be resolved in favor
of the AGPLv3's applicability.
